        <h3>Understanding Breast Cancer</h3>
        <p>
          Breast cancer occurs when abnormal cells grow uncontrollably in breast tissue.
          It can affect both women and men, although it is far more common in women.
        </p>
        <p>
          Early detection significantly improves treatment success and survival rates.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="article-section">
        <h3>Common Signs & Symptoms</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Lump in the breast or underarm</li>
          <li>Change in breast size or shape</li>
          <li>Nipple discharge (especially bloody)</li>
          <li>Skin dimpling, redness, or thickening</li>
          <li>Persistent breast pain</li>
        </ul>
      </article>

      <article class="article-section">
        <h3>Risk Factors</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Family history of breast cancer</li>
          <li>Increasing age</li>
          <li>Obesity and lack of physical activity</li>
          <li>Smoking and excessive alcohol intake</li>
        </ul>
      </article>

      <article class="article-section">
        <h3>Myths vs Facts</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Myth:</strong> Breast cancer is caused by witchcraft</li>
          <li><strong>Fact:</strong> Breast cancer is a medical condition</li>
          <li><strong>Myth:</strong> All breast lumps are cancer</li>
          <li><strong>Fact:</strong> Many lumps are benign, but must be checked</li>
        </ul>
      </article>

